article.description:
Kevin Garnett had 23 points, 15 rebounds and
six assists, and Anthony Peeler scored a season-high 17 points as
the Minnesota Timberwolves held off the Los Angeles Lakers 110-107
Sunday night.
article.headline: Timberwolves get first win visiting Lakers since 1993

images.name: Garnett Kevin 021201 inline
images.caption: Kevin Garnett helps the Timberwolves pick up their fifth win in seven games.

article.linkText: Garnett, reserves allow T-Wolves to edge Lakers
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- For the first time in nine years and only the third time ever, the Minnesota Timberwolves celebrated a victory over the Lakers in Los Angeles. But not before they nearly blew an eight-point lead in the last 41 seconds. Kevin Garnett had 23 points, 15 rebounds and six assists, and Anthony Peeler scored a season-high 17 points as the Timberwolves held off the three-time defending champions 110-107 Sunday night. Minnesota had lost 16 in a row to the Lakers on the road since winning by two points in December 1993. Overall, the Timberwolves have a 3-23 road record against the Lakers. ''It's a long time since we've won here,'' said the 26-year-old Garnett, who was a junior in high school when it last happened. ''You've got to think to yourself, 'It's going to happen sooner or later.' It's a good feeling. ''We know the Lakers are good. At the same time, we're trying to instill some confidence in ourselves.'' Kobe Bryant had a chance to tie the game when he was fouled by Joe Smith while taking a 3-point shot with 7.2 seconds left, but after making the first two free throws, he missed the third. Smith got the rebound, was fouled, and made the first foul shot. He missed the second, but Kendall Gill got the rebound, was fouled, and made another free throw to complete the scoring. Guarded closely by Gill, Bryant missed the rim on a wild 3-pointer as time expired. The Lakers had to rush down the floor because they were out of timeouts. ''It's a great win,'' Gill said. ''Anytime you can beat the champions on their home floor, it's a great win.'' Of his key rebound -- one of two he had in the game -- Gill said: ''I just went up and got it, jumped as high as I could. I'm 34, I can still get up there.'' Reserves sparked the Timberwolves in the fourth quarter, with Smith scoring seven of his 14 points, Rod Strickland six of his eight and Peeler adding four. Smith made a pair of jumpers to spark an 11-2 run by the Timberwolves, which Garnett capped by hitting two free throws with 2:06 left to make it 102-95. Garnett's foul shot with 41 seconds left made it 105-97, but Shaquille O'Neal scored five points and Bryant made a 3-pointer with 10.9 seconds left to cut Minnesota's lead to 106-105. Gill, who scored all nine of his points in the fourth quarter, made two foul shots before Bryant was fouled by Smith while attempting a 3-pointer. ''It's hard to make three in a row,'' Lakers coach Phil Jackson said. ''He's not shooting free throws really well right now anyway.'' Bryant has made 78 percent of his foul shots this season. ''The third one didn't fall for me,'' he said. ''It rattled in and just came out. I guess it just wasn't meant to be. It's like Tiger (Woods) putting and the thing just hits the lip and rolls off.'' Troy Hudson added 16 points for the Timberwolves (10-8), who have won five of their last seven games. O'Neal led the Lakers (6-12) with 31 points and 13 rebounds. Bryant had 22 points and 11 assists and Rick Fox added 13 points for the Lakers, who are 6-12 overall and 3-3 since O'Neal returned from the injured list. ''We're kind of beating ourselves, shooting ourselves in the foot,'' O'Neal said. ''This is just another game that we gave up tonight and it's just about us, we made silly mistakes.'' The Timberwolves outscored the Lakers 15-2 to finish the third quarter and start the fourth for a 79-76 lead, and Strickland made two free throws to cap a 6-0 run and make it 89-82. But O'Neal scored five points to spark an 11-2 spurt by the Lakers, giving them a 93-91 lead with 5:18 to play. That's when the Timberwolves began their winning rally. Neither team led by more than five points before the Lakers outscored the Timberwolves 10-2 to finish the second quarter for a 60-50 halftime lead. Game notes
The Lakers activated forward Devean George, who missed 10 games because of tendinitis in his right ankle. George, who had eight points in 17 minutes, started the season's first seven games, averaging 11.7 points. ... To make room on their roster, the Lakers placed rookie guard Jannaro Pargo on the injured list because of tendinitis in his right knee. ... Lakers forward Robert Horry missed his second consecutive game because of soreness in his left foot and right Achilles'. ... Los Angeles reserves, who scored only three points in a 112-106 overtime victory at Memphis on Friday night, had 15 in the first half against the Timberwolves and 21 overall. ... The Timberwolves have beaten only two teams with winning records. All their defeats have come to teams with winning records.
